<LP>
   LONDON -- New consumer credit extended by finance houses,
building societies, other specialist credit grantors and
retailers totaled a seasonally adjusted #3.97 billion ($6.95
billion) in May, up from #3.69 billion in April and #3.58
billion in May 1989, the Central Statistical Office said.
   The amount of consumer credit outstanding in May totaled
#28.12 billion, compared with #27.79 billion in April and
#25.49 billion in May 1989.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the three months through May, new consumer credit
extended rose 3% to #11.39 billion from #11.04 billion in the
previous three months.
   Fixed-sum lending to consumers was #1.55 billion in May,
up from #1.43 billion in April and from #1.48 billion in May
1989. The amount of fixed-sum lending outstanding in May rose
#196 million to #20.22 billion, compared with April's rise of
#94 million to #20.03 billion.
   Lending through bank credit cards rose to #2.29 billion in
May from #2.19 billion in April and #2.02 billion in May
1989. The amount of credit card lending outstanding in May
rose #77 million to #7.19 billion, compared with a rise in
April of #39 million to #7.11 billion.
</TEXT>
